review.reviewBody:
I picked a pair of Climb 2.0s back in October 2020 and have logged about 175,000 feet of vert of them since then. They have held up very well only showing some loss of felting around the tails and a few stitches that attach the tail strap coming undone. The glue is still tacky and confidence-inspiring. 

The glide is super smooth and the grip is solid. They do tend to slide on glazed-up skin tracks especially compared to my old nylon skins.
review.name: Great everyday skin

review.reviewBody: Bought these instead of my usual Contour Mix since my local shop didn't have the size I needed in stock, and I'd heard good things about Pomoca. Wish I'd held out or ordered online. I've skied about 10 days on these. The plush is fine and glides well enough, but it's already showing signs of wear, with patches of missing plush. The glue is decent and sticks well enough, though I prefer the smooth, easy pull-apart of Contour's hybrid glue. The hardware is where these skins really let me down. The tip attachment on one skin has almost completely fallen apart. Granted, the first crack occurred after catching the wire bail with the other ski's tip mid-stride, but I've done this plenty of times with other skins and never had issues. Aside from the bail itself, the attachment is made of cheap, thin plastic, and the small crack has spread such that the entire attachment has broken apart. Woof. And the tail clip design is, in my opinion, terrible - it requires a lot of fiddling to get it to lock on to the ski, and it's needlessly difficult to adjust the length. I've read stories of the stitching on the tail clips failing completely, and given that the stitching on one of my skins is nowhere near centered, I wouldn't be surprised if mine failed as well. Overall I doubt these skins will last more than a full season, and that's assuming the inevitable epoxy job on the busted tip attachment holds up. Maybe the higher end Pomoca models are better, but I'll be sticking with Contour going forward.
review.name: Seriously unimpressed

name: Climb 2.0 Climbing Skins

review.reviewBody: Being an older slim, but shorter active Pickleball player has presented a problem with other T-Shirt brands. I spent my summer having to cut off lengths on most of what I could find, and hemming my tops - that is until I found these great Tops. So I have purchased every color available in both the short and long - sleeved.  The length, fit, fabric and composition are par excellence.  They wash beautifully. Feel great on the skin - in fact PERFECT.
review.name: Best find in T-Shirts

review.reviewBody: I love this tee so much, slightly cropped, incredibly soft. Washes well and will be getting this as a closet staple both long and short sleeve. Great for layering or on its own, for work or play. BONUS The Egret color NOT transparent which is a win in my book! Do not hesitate, so worth a try!
review.name: Soft quality basic

review.reviewBody: I love this top. It’s comfortable, well-made, and is a perfect length for me. I like tops that are slightly cropped. They are perfect for wearing with joggers. I bought the green and it’s a very pretty color. I hope Backcountry continues making this top and will also add more colors. For size reference, I’m 5’ 4.5”, 99 lbs, and the XS is a perfect fit. All my Backcountry brand apparel fits perfectly.
review.name: It’s perfect!

review.reviewBody: I have the short sleeve version and decided to get the long sleeved one because I liked it so much! These shirts are super soft, and very slightly cropped, which I LOVE! It's hard as a shorter person to find outdoors/ athletic shirts that aren't super long. Please make more colors!
review.name: Great, soft shirt!

review.reviewBody: The overall fit, fabric, and sleeve length on this tee are amazing. But why is it a crop length? The last thing I’m looking for in a long sleeve for travel or hiking is less coverage, and the length is mentioned nowhere in the description. Please make the women’s destination tees in a regular length.
review.name: Why is this cropped???

review.reviewBody: So far it is great. It has all the features I needed allowing me to carry all my traveling clothes, shoes and snorkeling gear. The only thing I would change and I'm not sure how (just the nature of the type of bag) would be when carrying as a backpack if there would be a way to stop the swinging from side to side. But other than that it is a great product and an awesome bag.

review.reviewBody: This bag is exactly what I was looking for. Perfect size for a weeks plus worth of traveling. I wanted a backpack duffle that was durable and lightweight. This checks both boxes. And the color is great!
review.name: Travel Bag

review.reviewBody: always wanted to get a travel duffel for my trips and Allpa checks all the boxes from being practical to aesthetic. i love how it packs up to a small bag so i can bring it along during my travels!
review.name: Aesthetic travel duffle

review.reviewBody: We love these bags for our family of 4. We wear things hard and these hold up. We love our 70L (fit in our Thule car topper perfectly) for travel but the 50L is the perfect size for a carryon during long weekend plane trips without having to check any luggage.
review.name: Great bag, great size

review.reviewBody: Needed a new bag for some upcoming trips in the coming year and stumbled on the Allpa 50L. Biggest draw was the size of the bag itself and the organization. Great size and more than enough space for weekend trips for a family of three. I chose the Smoke/Cinder color which is slightly darker/more gray than pictured on the website and I love the color! Absolutely also love the amount of organization in the bag itself and how durable it feels. Definitely sleek enough to take on a regular vacation but also sturdy enough to throw around on a camping/road trip!
review.name: Solid Gear Bag

review.reviewBody: Love all my Cotopaxi gear (including this duffle). Everything is high quality and lasts through activities.
review.name: Quality

review.reviewBody:
Tested on 2 back to back trips of 5 nights total across the country for work and pleasure so had to fit in running gear, casual/social gear, work gear and the usual toiletries etc. Performed very well. Not problems with carry on on Alaska. Comfortable to wear on the back around the airport. Really good selection of different pockets for smaller items and I like the bottom compartment for smelly running gear. Zippers are robust and super smooth. The grab handle at the end of really useful and the fact that when you swing it down off your back it land the right way up because the straps are at the top is well-thought. The top straps don't really get in the way of opening the main compartment either. 
I would have like straps to compress the pack a bit but then you end up with too many straps overall I suppose.
Excellent product and really happy with the purchase.
review.name: Tested and love it. Perfect size, well designed and built.

review.reviewBody: This product was exactly what we were looking for! Durable and well made. My husband loved it for his surfing trip. Perfect!
review.name: Excellent!

review.reviewBody: I love that this bag allows you to carry it in so many different ways - it's truly versatile. The separated bottom compartment is great. It seems to be very durable and well made. Very happy with the purchase!
review.name: Love this duffle

review.reviewBody: It was returned immediately returned after discovering that the handles were covered in mold. I got a refund rather than a replacement because it was clear that the design would be prone to this since the fabric handles were within a non breathable pocket. Seem prone to mold if exposed to significant moisture with the handles in the pockets. It was also surprisingly heavy in comparison. Surprised when I opened it up and then specs vs competitors afterwards confirmed it. Unfortunate since I was very excited for this bag’s potential.
review.name: Part showed up covered in mold

review.reviewBody: I purchased a 6L sling this past year and used it while on travel and really like it a lot. However, I found it limiting and wanted a small bag to help me lug my mirrorless camera and 3 lens (8-16mm, 70-300mm, and 16-80mm) all day without fatigue around neck and shoulder. The sling doesn't start out heavy, but it gets heavy when you are lugging it all day and switching between lenses while walking through new cities. I chose this backpack because it is 20L...smaller than my 45L backpack and bigger than the 6L sling...I also liked the continuous zipper design. I received the bag. It looks and feels great. The option to open from the top looked good in the video, but in reality, the bag doesn't have a natural bend toward the top and I found it hard to access its contents without fully unzipping the bag. The only problem with trying to open the bag is the dividers have to be detached from the top of the bag. This is not ideal. The last and biggest problem I had is the bag simply did not sit well on my back. I have a broad back. I am a big guy. The bag is entirely too small for it to be ergonomically pleasing. The shoulder straps fully extended caused the bag to sit low on my back toward my butt. This made it impossible to use the chest strap.
review.name: Great concept...bag not built for my body type

review.reviewBody: I bought this about a year ago with photography in mind, but I have been surprised since then to see the versatility of the bag! You can use it for absolutely anything, with no worries at all knowing that it made to the high Peak Design quality.
review.name: Best All-Round Backpack

review.reviewBody: Yeah so I got this for my brother for graduation and he was familiar with the brand and wanted this backpack for a while. So I got it and have been watching him. Frankly it’s ok maybe a bit overpriced for what you get but definitely nice. Would recommend
review.name: Pretty good

review.reviewBody:
I love the pretty design of the bag, and it's very convenient for daily use.
The zipper is good, but a more durable material could be better.
review.name: Great Design Nice Outlook

review.reviewBody: Recently received this new Everyday Zip and I am finding it the perfect size to get back & forth to the office w/my 13” laptop and iPad. Easy access to the laptop pocket w/o having to open the entire bag. Top/side access and moveable shelves allows me to visit for my papers and accessories.
review.name: Multiple Pockets/Multiple Zippers

review.reviewBody:
My first words to anyone when talking about this bag are always "It's got shelves!"
It's everything a tech-type needs. Customisable, compartments, capacity... I also love the design. Almost 360° access - it's my favourite bag and travels with me everywhere.
review.name: My favourite bag - it's got shelves!!

review.reviewBody: This brilliantly thought out backpack has revolutionised my mobile office needs - it is a personal organiser that truly helps me take everything that I need from one office to another and one business to another. I no longer loose things in the bottom of a bag or leave things in the wrong office, or waste time trying to go through endless pockets because everything has a place, nothing gets wet, magnets and zips mean nothing falls out, no-one can dip a hand into it or steal anything out of it in a crowd or on public transport. I put it on its side on a chair next to me and it is like a personal filing cabinet and I strap it on with a loop round the back of the chair so it doesnt fall over with all the contents on the floor. I have only had it for a week but it is extremely robust and even when heavy and full it is very comfortable on my back. I love it and would happily take it on holiday hiking except that I would have to empty it to reload - and how healthy is it to take a workplace essential on holiday with you?
review.name: Excellent - my mobile office in a perfect bag

review.reviewBody: Très pratique et surtout très léger, les compartiments sont modulables pour séparer correctement toutes mes affaires. Seul bémol : il faut que le sac soit vide pour bien repositionner chaque séparateur.
review.name: Le meilleur sac que j’ai eu

review.reviewBody: I have struggled for years to find a camera bag that doesn’t look like a camera bag! This changed that and I won’t ever use another bag again. It’s so well made, practical, masses of space for a small bag and looks amazing
review.name: The best non camera bag looking camera bag

review.reviewBody:
This backpack can easily store headphones, Sony alpha dslr, extra lens, iPad Pro, and has an awesome privacy compartment for passport plus iPhone or cash. 
This is my go to travel bag and is just what I was looking for in terms of being able to access my dslr quickly and put it away.
review.name: Fantastic backpack for everything

review.reviewBody: Pants fit nice and look super good. Comfortable and stylish, make you look sleek and not pudgy! I’m happy to go with a size medium, Im usually in between M-L for pants so it’s a plus to size down lol. They are actually loose around the waist and roomy in other places, but they fit well around my hips and butt. Def size down if you’re contemplating it. Im 5’10 155lbs, 33” inseam on legs if that helps. I got regular length and they fit down to my boot perfectly.
review.name: Nice stylish comfy!

review.reviewBody: Perfect length for 5’4-5’6.  Both of my hard-charging teen daughters wear these pants.  They have held up to a lot of abuse and keep everyone warm and dry.
review.name: A perfect insulated ski pant

review.reviewBody: The pants look great, and are very well-insulated. 5’5”, 130 lbs.;  bought size small, regular length. A bit roomy in the waist, even with the Velcro adjustment. The length is about perfect with boots on. They are “Glacier” color, which should actually be “dirty glacier”, as they appear much more white in the pictures than the light gray color they actually are. But that’s about all the bad there is about them thus far.
review.name: Fire fit!

review.reviewBody: I am an avid fan of MH clothing.  So, i ordered my usual and was unfortunately disappointed.  These pants fit well from a size perspective.  The insulation is just right and they don't make you feel like a marshmallow.  But they are way too short!  I had to return...
review.name: Way too short

review.reviewBody: I ordered these in a M given all the reviews about them running small.  They were HUGE. the legs, waist, everything. I am 6' and a thin/athletic build with a rear and it looked like I had an XL on with these. They were long enough, which I did appreciate.  Also, the material and construction were also very good quality.
review.name: strange fit - nice quality

review.reviewBody: I purchased pants to go with the jacket but hated the jacket. Didn’t love the pants either. They are a bit bulky and material itself is stiff. I am 5,4 and they were a tad short on me. I am regular M but the pants were a little tight around the waist when put on base layer, usually don’t have this issue. Can’t speak for the warmth  as I didn’t use outside but I wouldn’t be comfortable skiing in them, can be on for snow play.
review.name: Has nice feature but uncomfortable

review.reviewBody: These are great ski pants!  I love the color and features. I had to return because the size was too large, and unfortunately they were out of stock in the size I needed. For reference, I'm generally a size 4-6 and ordered a Medium so I could wear a layer underneath if needed. The M was too large on me, so I think the S would have been perfect. Keeping an eye out for them to be restocked!
review.name: Great quality and color

name: FireFall/2 Insulated Pant - Women's

review.reviewBody:
Coming from a size small in other Castelli bibs, this one was a squeeze to get into. But once on, it's nicely compressive. The chamois is nicely padded and felt comfortable for the 4 hour rides I've taken it on. The hip panels protected from abrasion as advertised when I had a minor wreck.

The pockets are nice and fit a decent amount of items.

Deducted one star for the size discrepancy from other Castelli bibs and for some rough seams. At this price point, I expect the finish to be better.

review.reviewBody:
Seems very well made, but they are impossibly small. I used the size chart; I got the size I ordered, but they were very tight. I was hoping if I wore them a few times they might ease up a bit, but no such luck. It is a real a shame since the pad seems particularly plush. I successfully purchase all kinds of clothing from a variety of brands and have never had this problem with shorts/bibs.
review.name: Impossibly Tight

review.reviewBody:
Ordered these Castelli bibs in XL and they were at least one, maybe two sizes too small! 

I have worn Castelli bibs in XL for almost 10 years. I typically wear L in US-made cycling gear, XL in Euro-made gear. Just bought a pair of Assos bib shorts in XL and they fit fine (I could have fit into the L). I have not changed shape or size for several years.  

Also did not like the feel of the protection panels, it is stiffer than lycra, feels like plastic.
review.name: Small sizing even for Castelli!

review.itemreviewed: Ultra Raptor II Mid Leather GTX Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody:
I really wanted to like these shoes, but was disappointed by the sloppy shoe construction. QC at the La Sportiva factory must have been on vacation when these shoes were made. There were obvious dried glue marks and blobs along the rand and midsole. There was also a small gap between the plastic heel counter and the bottom of one shoe, and a drop of orange paint on another shoe.

Aside from construction issues, I would have preferred a real heel loop and metal lace hooks. The shoe definitely runs small. I wear a US 9.5 narrow and the EU 41.5 was too small for me. Go up at least a half size to try this shoe.

The Ultra Raptor II isn't all bad, though. I really appreciated how light these shoes are; they won't weigh you down for a day of hiking. They're fairly attractive and not too stiff. They won't require much breaking-in at all.
review.name: Shoe Quality Doesn't Match the Price

review.reviewBody: I often heard how great and comfortable Sidi, shoes were. I logged less than 200 miles on them and they were just not comfortable! Nothing good to say about this shoe except I liked the color! I should have stayed with my S Works! Head and shoulders more comfortable!
review.name: Disappointing shoe

review.reviewBody: I should have bought top of the line Sidis as I have for years . The Boa’s on the right shoe just come loose and the tongue falls off to the side..
review.name: Grea Sidi fit but Boa's come loose..

review.reviewBody: These Sidi shoes have fit very well right out of the box. I have 2 hotspots that aren't bad and if they go away like I think they will, they will be a 5 star shoe in my opinion. The service  and shipping was spot on and one more reason I keep using Competitive Cycling. Thank you.
review.name: Working on a 5th Star

review.reviewBody: I was unsure about the sizing even after speaking with a sales rep. I decided to buy two different sizes hoping one would work. Unfortunately, neither worked. Therefore, I had to order a third pair. Third time was almost a charm. They fit everywhere except the hill. I had to much room and this model doesn't have the hill adjestment. Nice looking shoe and on sale was a great buy.
review.name: I've always wanted a pair of Sidi's

review.reviewBody: I've got a few hundred miles on these shoes. Fit is true to size, and plenty of toe/forefoot room, which is exactly what I was looking for to replace some custom-made road shoes that I eventually 'grew out of'. I like the retention system (Boa-like, but not true Boa as described on the webpage), the softness of the uppers, the overall looks. There's one down-side if you're looking for a really stiff sole: the sole is carbon-injected, not a true full carbon sole. If you're a sprinter and really put power to the pedals, this may be a drawback. But if you're a fast recreational cyclists who doesn't really sprint, I doubt you'll find the sole to be an issue. I sure don't. Giving 4 stars because of the sole issue, otherwise for me personally, it gets at least 4.5 stars. This shoe is a good value. I recommend it.
review.name: A good shoe for a non-elite cyclist

review.reviewBody: Got 4 flats in 6 months, I've never had as many flats with any other tires, 3 of them have been tubeless. They work great on pavement and on light gravel, I got no traction on different terrain tho, I really liked them but can't give 5 stars with so many flats.
review.name: Great tires, too many flats

review.reviewBody: Second set I've owned durable! Ride though any terrain !
review.name: Gravel kings

review.reviewBody: Even though these have the name GravelKing don't mistake these for some knobby tires that can attack everything from packed dirt, mud, to chunky loose bits.  Yes 42mm will give you a lot of comfort and allow you to travel on some very basic "gravel" that a slick 28" wouldn't be great on but in essence these are just a very big slick tire.  For me these tires are great for concrete gravel, which is riding on bumpy broken tarmac.  The low resistance allows you to get some good speed while running lower pressure, which means really great comfort.  The 42mm version at 700g is fairly light but with the minimal tread these tires do need to be replaced a bit quicker than other tires.  So if you understand that these aren't really Gravel tires and you are okay with that my only real complaint is that these tires are tacky (great for traction) but when fresh they attract leaf bits like crazy.  I am 140lbs and I recommend using 50-60 PSI, 50 (slightly bellow recommended) when you want more of that cushy life and 60 PSI when you are road riding.
review.name: Gravel tire? No but a great slick tire

review.reviewBody:
My gravel bike was purchased more for the versatility and comfort fatter tires afford than the expectation of doing a lot of gravel riding, and while the WTB Byways the bike came with are great in almost every way, I wanted something with a bit less heft and rolling resistance and more road friendliness. 

The first outing on these GravelKings (650bX42) quickly proved to me that they will be my default tire for any ride that won't have me on gnarly surfaces. They roll quick, add noticeable comfort and handle very well. I'm a new fan. 

Great job, Panaracer!
review.name: My new default tires

review.reviewBody: Not sure if I got unlucky but the pair I received simply was not warm, regardless of time the heating element never warmed to anything I would call "warming."  Returned with no issues just not worth the cost and a shame from a brand I like
review.name: Not warm?

review.reviewBody: I've been skiing for 30 years and unfortunately have nerve damage in my fingers and toes due to multiple bouts of frostbite.  The Hestra rep steered me to these instead of the heated gloves due to durability.  The liner is great and comfortable but the battery system is an s show.  They're too bulky, difficult to keep in the liner, waaaay to big to pair with the cuffs of my Hestra Army gloves, and it's a pain to mate with my jacket cuff.  The phone app is a joke and doesn't offer much functionality.  I think this is an example of a first generation product missing the mark, by a wide margin.  I agree with everything the other reviewer (Law) stated in their synopsis.  I wouldn't recommend these liners for any reason.  Especially at this price.
review.name: Not A Good Product

review.reviewBody:
As someone who suffers from Raynauds, I'm always looking for good heated gloves.  I have a set of Outdoor Research that have served me well for 5-6 seasons, and wanted to update.  These gloves looked great--thin enough to wear as a liner, so I can layer up or down as needed.

Unfortunately, the magnetic attachment of the batteries is finicky and impossible to see, so you spend 5 minutes trying to attach the batteries.  Battery life on high is just a couple hours...so if you want a full day skiing, get used to low setting.  You can't get a duplicate set of batteries to swap out at this point...so utility is limited.

Most annoying is the design, however.  The batteries are way up on your forearm, attached to the stretchy gauntlet part of the glove, and there's no support for them.  They bounce around, droop down your arm, move and slide with every movement of your arms, etc.  Trying to fit them in the sleeve of your jacket is a PITA, and it becomes a 5 step process to put these on, get the jacket situated, get a waterproof glove on over it, fix the cuff, etc...only to have the batteries slide around the first time you move your arms.  Pass on these.  I'm typically a L in gloves and got these in 9 based on the size chart; fit was great.
review.name: Good idea, poor execution

name: Tactility Heat Liner Glove

review.reviewBody: This short is constructed of a very thin material, which is nice if you’re looking for a very light  weight, cool running/ activity short . There is no interior lining or brief. The pocket has a snap and is fine for a key, fob, some cash or a credit card. The pocket is too small and the shorts ( or rather, the waistband)  are likely too lightweight for a cell phone. The cut is not low waisted and the legs are a breezy, generous, open cut which is nice if you have a build  that tends to suck tighter and shorter shorts upwards. The fabric is delicate enough to snag and pill on barely rough surfaces like smooth wood or concrete benches.  Overall , not worth full price to me, but sufficient for a reduced price.
review.name: thin and breezy , breezy but thin

review.reviewBody:
Hot summer days hiking, here I come. Ordered a size too big, so I’m returning for one size down (getting a medium). I have thicker thighs so finding shorts that are a comfortable fit that aren’t too loose in the waist and too tight in the hips is.. a challenge. 

Fits higher on my hip than the multi-trails short and they’re lighter weight, which makes them perfect for my backpacking trips. I hate when the waistband rubs  into my hip from my pack, so I’m excited to have a higher waisted short that is also super comfy and airy!

review.reviewBody: I am a blind individual, and it is therefore always difficult to purchase the correct items online without getting to physically handle them first. However, Outdoor Research gear has always been reliable and trusted by me. The description of the alpine merino liners on the wetsite was great, and the measuring chart also was exact. Therefore I could purchase the correct size, and had a good idea of the product I was purchasing. I live in the Boston area and have used my liner to go hiking during very windy and cold days. In particular, I was blown away with how the liners performed during a wet and windy hike. I wore my liner and rain pants, and even though the wind made it feel like temperature was in the single digits during my hike my legs were perfectly warm. The liner has also served me well during more practical day-to-day situations like waiting for an Uber in downtown Boston during a windy day at rush hour. Also, the liner is extremely comfortable and I have found that it feels good whether I am wearing it under my jeans or at home by itself. Construction is durable and seems like it will last for a long time; many years of hiking and day-to-day use. Definitely a recommended item from a brand that never disappoints!
review.name: Warm, comfortable, and well made!

review.reviewBody: I was so excited about this purchase as the overalls are very cute and fit well.  But, alas, they are not made well.  1) the pieces of metal that are supposed to keep the overall attached to the chest button were cheap.  They kept popping off and I ended up losing one after having to grab my kiddo off the monkey bars quickly.  I have other overalls and have never had this problem.  In fact I took one off of one overall and put it on this one, using a pliers, it worked well (were the pliers didn't do a thing on original piece).  2) After only 1.5 wears, the seem at the crotch and at the ankle is coming a part. Sad too cause I liked the zipper component, that was an improvement on my regular overalls.  3) I now need to figure out how I can return them without the original packaging which is a very disappointing timesuck.

review.itemreviewed: Mille GTS Spring Fall C2 Jacket - Men's
review.reviewBody:
Your arm warmers today.  Or your wind vest.  I’ve owned one version or another of this jacket or jersey for almost 20 years and I always use more than I think I will.   The windproof and waterproof front panel are great for those days when it’s not going to break 60 or if it might rain a little. 

The fabric in the sleeves is super comfortable and luxurious.  Not too much insulation but just enough that some wind will get through.

The back is basically cycling jersey fabric and super breathable.

The cut of the jacket leaves more room than previous versions, particularly in the chest, so do not size up needlessly.  The jacket does not fit nearly as close as the GT Jerseys do so there’s plenty of room for a layer.  My preference is a closer fit which is the only reason why it’s not 5 stars.  

I wear this jacket when the temp is between 46 and 62 and swap out various levels of base layers.  I prefer to be a little warmer when I ride, which is to say that I do not like feeling like I need to ride harder to stay warmer—I’d rather unzip than wish I had a warmer layer.
review.name: Because You’re Probably Not Taking Off

I bought the Amber 44 a month ago for an overnight backpacking. It’s great and it fit everything I needed.I like that it has adjustable back hight and I liked the chest strap, adjustable hight as well. The backpack is sturdy, the material is great and the rain cover is good, even though I would have appreciated more a cord that I can tie, instead if the elastic on the margins. Also, for securing the raincover, a longer strap would have come in handy, the one existent is too small to close when on a full backpack. 
Downsides I found: the hipbelt pockets are a but small and they don’t fit well my phone (iPhone SE, not even big); also they are a bit hard to access, positioned more towards the back. The hipbelt itself, no matter the position, hurt my hips, because the padded area is too short and the plastic elements don’t sit on any padding, but on your iliac crest and I ended up with bruises. 
Another downside is that if the backpack is not full, the top part saggs.
And the last one: when full, the backpack is squeaking, i believe the frame and the upper cap junction..

review.reviewBody:
Tried several systems over the years for saltwater flats fishing. Landed on this over Patagonia designs and other smaller brands. Use it with Plano dry boxes (3540) for conventional lures/terminal tackle, and keep plastics in their various baggies.

Right balance in storage room, having enough for a small hard lure box, terminal tackle box (hooks/jig heads/ snaps/ etc), and plastics bags, but not too much room that it becomes a burden when wading. Personally use it as a sling-style over back and bring it around to front when needed. 

Only improvement would be the loop front for lures. Really like it as of now, but for longevity of use (can see ripping and adding lures off it not lasting too long), is to switch to either replaceable foam panel or stronger magnet panel like other tackle organizers out there. Great product otherwise!
review.name: Great Pack with Some Considerations

review.reviewBody: Received 04-12 and worn once., Waistbelt will not maintain tightness and loosens while wearing. It kept slipping off my waist in the river due to poor design. Simms refuses to refund because it's used. Simms products fill my closet and have always been my favorite line but will not have the next 30 yrs. of my fishing business due to poor customer service policies!
review.name: Falls off

review.reviewBody: I like this pack and all its features. I have one complaint: the belt straps are very annoying. When you try to slide the pack to your front or push it back behind you, it gets caught, making it hard to slide on your waist. This is because the waist straps are connected to the pack, so moving the pack involves moving the straps, and the friction between your straps and your hips makes it difficult. I have no idea why it was built this way. It is the only hip pack Simms makes with the waistbelt stitched into the pack. To get 5 stars, all Simms would need to do is attach loops to the pack and a waistbelt going through that so it would slide on the belt for easier access.
review.name: Pretty good Waist belt sucks.

review.reviewBody: I bought this pack for trout fishing on day trips or to be stuffed in a rucksack for backpacking trips. The belt does not stay tight on your waist. With minimal movement the belt loosens and falls to the ground. Wearing it over the shoulder is a better option but when you net fish it flops all over as there is no stabilizing strap to secure your body. It just doesn’t seem like anyone who actually fishes had anything to do with the design of this bag. Throughly disappointed.
review.name: Throughly Disappointed

review.reviewBody: Enough room for everything I need during predator fishing day. Thank You Simms. You are doing great products.
review.name: Best for predator fishing

name: Tributary Hip Pack

review.reviewBody:
I’m a big fan of the MSR brand, and I’ve always appreciated the quality of your products. My first tent was the MSR Elixir 3, and two years ago, I decided to get the Hubba Hubba 2-person tent as my second. I haven’t used it extensively, but overall, I’ve been very happy with it. The tent is incredibly lightweight, waterproof, wind-resistant, and offers plenty of space.

However, this year, during a 7-day trek on the Lycian Way in Turkey, I encountered an issue. On the third day, one of the carbon poles broke. Thankfully, a friend had repair splints with them, which saved the situation. Without that, I would have been in serious trouble, as I still had 4 days of remote trekking ahead.

It’s surprising that repair splints weren’t included in the tent’s package, especially considering its price point. I expected the poles to last longer under normal use.

review.itemreviewed: Last Chair Stretch Insulated Anorak - Men's
review.reviewBody:
Got this just before the 23/24 season. I generally prefer insulated jackets instead of shells so it's easier to pack up, and I was intrigued by the blew color of this jacket! Sizing is spot on, with just a tad extra room to add layers underneath or for increased mobility. I'm 5'11" and 230 lbs and the XL was perfect for me.

The warmth is perfect, and the ventilation options are pretty good. There's a full length zipper to mid arm for entry/exit, and the other size has a little shorter length zipper for venting, but still vents over the pits so not too bad there. Opening the main pocket also allows some venting so while I was warm I was never overheating. The jacket is also surprisingly flexible, and so far I've had zero rips or issues, plus it's mostly waterproof (haven't had any super wet sessions but I was never wet at least).

I've really only got two complaints about this otherwise perfect jacket. Like the other reviewer, I found the inner hand liners to be a bit short. When you put them on it really pulls on the stitching and it feels like it will rip. It seems to be attached just before the wrist, and the first few uses I heard audibly some stitches popping. I stopped using them after that and didn't find it to be too big of an issue. The second is that the main pouch zipper gets stuck frequently. It's not catching on fabric (though sometimes it does) but it just doesn't want to work, and it's always when trying to close the pocket instead of on open. Additionally, it could use a separate zipper on this pocket so you get access from both directions. I'm right-handed, but the zipper pulls left to open. So to open the pocket you need to use your left hand or do an awkward push with the right. It would be nice to have a second zipper that goes the other way so you have options.

In any case, I would still highly recommend this jacket. Got it on sale for just over $100 and it well exceeds the quality of the price I paid!
review.name: Fantastic Jacket w/ Just a Few Quirks

review.itemreviewed: Last Chair Stretch Insulated Anorak - Men's
review.reviewBody:
First, I love the style and color of this jacket. It’s plenty warm with pit zips and side vents if you get warm. The downfalls are basically one giant pocket and no pockets inside the jacket. Also no powder skirt kinda sucks. The worst thing about this jacket for me though was that the hood has no way of being secured, and just flaps around when bombing down the mountain. The other negative for me personally Is that the arms felt short—so when I used the wrist gaiters, they pulled on my thumbs when I was fully extending my arms and I felt like I was going to rip them out of the sleeves. 

For reference I’m about 6’3” and 230 pounds and I tried the XL. Ultimately I returned the jacket.
review.name: Pretty good but not good enough.

name: Last Chair Stretch Insulated Anorak - Men's

Great gift.

This hoodie is cozy and warm and has become my new favorite go to in the chilly weather. 
I would definitely size down one size.

review.reviewBody:
I purchased this jacket to wear inside my house in the winter. I wore it outside in 30 degree weather with a smartwool woolen shirt underneath. It didn't keep me warm enough during my 5 mile walk. It was fine in 43 degree weather though. 
I wished it came in solid colors instead of the flannel designs. At least one inside pocket would have been a plus as well as would an extra 1/2"-1" length on the sleeves.
All in all, I love this super comfortable jacket. 
To help others with sizing, I purchased a small. I am 5'3-1/2" and weigh 126 lbs. I can fit a shirt and lightweight sweatshirt underneath the jacket.

review.itemreviewed: Waterproof All Weather Ultra Grip Knitted Glove
review.reviewBody: I was looking for gloves that could keep my dexterity while being reasonably water proof. These will get wet eventually, but I believe I could have remained warm and dry for most camp and skiing chores. However, the sizing is weird, as many others commented on other sites. You need long, very slender fingers for these to work. I was almost going to keep them and just keep pulling them back on my hands. However, the palms are large and baggy.  I am a girl, 5’3, 118 and bought a small.
review.name: Wish they fit, they could be perfect

review.itemreviewed: Waterproof All Weather Ultra Grip Knitted Glove
review.reviewBody: These are tagged as Mens gloves- but package says Unisex so one would expect Ladies to size down.  Too say these run small to not begin to capture the bizarre shape of these gloves, I dont think an 8 year old could fit into these gloves.  I ordered the small and see picture the pinkey fingers are 1.5 inches long and the index is 2.25 inches long.  And the gloves are abnormally wide! I dont know any human that would fit Into these.  Disappointed as i expect Backcountry to vet these products especially at this price point
review.name: Poor quality - bizarre shape

review.itemreviewed: Waterproof All Weather Ultra Grip Knitted Glove
review.reviewBody:
I have somewhat big hands, and ordered a medium (assumed it was in mens sizing). The thumb is a little long, but otherwise they fit great. I bought these for backcountry skiing and cold biking. So far I've used them biking in ~35-40 degree temps and they were very comfortable. 

I was impressed by their touch screen capabilities. It was like using my bare finger. When I took them out of the box, I was surprised by the material, and that it was supposed to be waterproof. I still haven't tested that, but so far they seem super durable. 

They also have long ends that more than adequately cover your wrists. I'm looking forward to seeing how these do skiing, preventing snow from getting up my jacket. 

Edit since using in the snow: 
These are very waterproof! Great for warm weather skiing and convenient to throw in my pack as an afternoon glove after a cold morning start.
review.name: Fit is a little big, but worked great

review.reviewBody: Just purchased a new replacement apex vest. Expecting one similar. No cinchable hemline drawstring in this new model! Only 50% as effective against wind, the descriptions still list as a feature! Wmmb
review.name: Bought a new replacement. Where's hem drawstring?

review.reviewBody: I bought this vest in the past and loved it, but I wore it out after a few years so I bought two more last year and was disappointed to find they are VERY tight around the chest, actually right below the pectoral area, when I put on the old one it fits perfectly, really disappointed as these must have been made incorrectly.
review.name: Too Tight Around the Chest

review.reviewBody: I'm pretty hard on my stuff. I buy quality because I simply dont like to shop. I picked this up in a mall and over the years I have tried to beat it down. I hike, alot. and its the perfect compliment to a thicker hoody, or small jacket.I regularly throw this sucker on the ground to sit on the inside of it, and there's no stains on it that havent washed out in one cylce. I'd definitely recommend it. I dont really leave comments either so, I guess it was compelling enough to do so.
review.name: I've owned this for years now, and its still perfect.

review.reviewBody: This vest is perfect for cooler weather. Length and fit are true to size. Great choice for my husband.
review.name: Yes

review.reviewBody: Overall great piece of gear. Plenty of pocket space, light weight, and works well with hoodies
review.name: I keep buying these things

review.reviewBody: Good material, sizes are funky. I initially order a size large, was very baggy and looked awkward, exchanged it for a size Medium, that was too tight in the shoulders with no stretch.
review.name: Funky sizing

review.reviewBody: it works well for the environment i am in. i recommend this vest.
